{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17633342","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17633342"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T17:51:47+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T17:51:47+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17472"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17472","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17472"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10162"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"70757"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10162","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10162"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17472"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"56223"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"5326"},{"type":"tags","id":"5360"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"23762"},{"type":"contributions","id":"23794"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"70757","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/70757"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EGender inequity remains a significant public health challenge in healthcare systems worldwide. Research shows that women often receive different standards of care compared to men presenting with the same symptoms.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes a documented consequence of gender inequity in healthcare?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Higher rates of preventive screening in women","Longer diagnostic delays for women with cardiovascular disease","More frequent pain management for women","Increased research funding for women\u0027s health conditions","Better mental health support for women"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe correct answer is that women experience \u003Cstrong\u003Elonger diagnostic delays for cardiovascular disease\u003C/strong\u003E. Research has consistently shown that women presenting with heart attack symptoms face longer waiting times for diagnosis and treatment compared to men with similar symptoms, often because their symptoms are attributed to anxiety or other non-cardiac causes.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHigher rates of preventive screening in women\u003C/strong\u003E: women face numerous barriers to accessing preventive care services, including cost, time constraints, and cultural factors.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMore frequent pain management for women\u003C/strong\u003E: research demonstrates that healthcare providers often underestimate and undertreat women\u0027s pain compared to men\u0027s pain reports.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIncreased research funding for women\u0027s health conditions\u003C/strong\u003E: medical research has historically focused predominantly on male subjects, with significantly less funding allocated to women\u0027s health issues.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBetter mental health support for women\u003C/strong\u003E: women encounter substantial barriers to mental healthcare access, including gender-based stigma, financial constraints, and systemic bias in diagnosis and treatment.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EGender inequity in healthcare manifests in multiple ways, including diagnostic delays, under-recognition of symptoms, and differences in treatment approaches. These disparities contribute to poorer health outcomes for women across various medical conditions.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Gender inequity in healthcare leads to worse health outcomes for women compared to men.","Implicit bias among healthcare providers contributes to gender-based differences in diagnosis and treatment.","Social determinants of health disproportionately affect women\u0027s access to healthcare globally."],"references":["Alcalde-Rubio, L., Hern\u00e1ndez-Aguado, I., Parker, L.A. et al. Gender disparities in clinical practice: are there any solutions? Scoping review of interventions to overcome or reduce gender bias in clinical practice. Int J Equity Health 19, 166 (2020). https://doi.org/10.1186/s12939-020-01283-4","Shultz JM, Sullivan LM, Galea S. Public Health: An Introduction to the Science and Practice of Population Health. Springer Publishing Company; 2021."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"56223"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17472"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"56223","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/56223"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-16T13:46:46+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-04T00:08:10+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10162"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"70757"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical studen